snippet.textDisplay: So an opportunity popped up with a really good find, so I went and bought it for $500!!! This really shows you what you can do to find your first project car, find a budget suv, etc with minimal risk and a lot of potential reward!!! We used all common hand tools and did this job at home ourselves! Craftsman was bought by Stanley and now they have decent tools for the price! Worth taking a look at for sure! I messed with the 150 piece set for the first time and I liked it. It got the job done and I think you guys looking for your first set would find it to be a good starter set! Here is the link to the tool sets: http://bit.ly/2PNfHLS

snippet.textDisplay: Thank you Chris! I always appreciate videos which specifically address a vehicle I happen to own. I especially appreciate someone who puts pride and effort into their craft as you do. Finally I applaud your effort to show the common car owner that they have the ability to do so much more for themselves than they thought. In today’s economy, the average person can’t afford to pay hundreds or thousands of dollars every time something goes wrong with their vehicle. I agree sometimes the fix will be too difficult or require more specialized tools or knowledge the owner does not possess. But often the repairs are not that difficult, the parts are relatively cheap but the labor cost makes the owner put off the repairs until they reach a potentially catastrophic condition. That is what I see in this vehicle, deferred maintenance and repair. If the previous owner had watched your videos, they may not have had to sell their car! Love your videos, keep up the good work!
